type="local"
href="alex-nelson.xml"
addr="alex-nelson"
title="Alex Nelson">Alex Nelson</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>We just need to prove this is a field morphism. It's clear <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\phi (1)=1]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\phi (xy)=xy]]></fr:tex>. We see:
<fr:tex
display="block"><![CDATA[\begin {align*} \phi (x+y) &= (x+y)^{p}\\ &= x^{p}+\binom {p}{1}x^{p-1}y+\binom {p}{2}x^{p-2}y^{2}+…+\binom {p}{1}xy^{p-1}+y^{p} \end {align*}]]></fr:tex>
We see if <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[0<k<p]]></fr:tex>, the numerator of the binomial coefficient <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\binom {p}{k}]]></fr:tex> is divisible by <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[p]]></fr:tex>, but not its denominator. Since <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\binom {p}{k}]]></fr:tex> is an integer, it must be a multiple of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[p]]></fr:tex>, hence equal to 0 in <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {F}]]></fr:tex>. Therefore
<fr:tex
display="block"><![CDATA[\phi (x+y)=x^{p}+y^{p}=\phi (x)+\phi (y).]]></fr:tex>
Hence <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\phi ]]></fr:tex> is a field morphism.</fr:p><html:span
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"
class="qed">∎</html:span></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree>
 

 
   
